  "text": "Animal Preparation and Monitoring. Male Wistar rats (259 Ϯ 42 g; Harlan, Horst, The Netherlands) were anesthetized with a mixture of ketamine (90 mg/kg), medetomidine (0.5 mg/kg), and atropine-sulfate (0.05 mg/kg) intraperitonally. A tracheostomy was performed, and the animals were mechanically ventilated (FIO 2 0.4). The right carotid artery was cannulated and used for monitoring of arterial blood pressure and heart rate. To allow continuous central venous pressure measurement, a catheter was inserted into the right jugular vein to a level of the right atrium. A catheter in the right femoral artery was used for withdrawal of blood via the right femoral vein for continuous infusion of Ringer's lactate (15 mL/kg/h; Baxter, The Netherlands) and ketamine (50 mg/kg/h; Nimatek; Eurovet, The Netherlands). Rectal temperature was maintained at 37°C. Through flank incision, the left kidney was exposed, decapsulated, and immobilized. Left RBF was measured with a perivascular flow probe connected to a flow meter (T206; Transonic Systems, Ithaca, NY). The left ureter was isolated, ligated, and cannulated for urine collection. At the end of the experiment, the left kidney was removed and weighed. All preceding steps are described in detail in a previous study [CITATION_1] .",
